Streams are more safer since they take care of all possible mishaps for you(but can crash your program if you dont catch their exceptions which is if you allowed them
to throw exceptions using "stream.exceptions()"). println/getline  is however very 
manual but also very portable(as portable as streams), infact std::println(stdout, "string") or std::getline(stdin, destination_variable) both are portable. 
Both of them also look better for some developers. Println and getline can be used with streams: std::println(std::cout, "string") or std::getline(std::cin, destination_variable).
For actual File IO as on 4-20-2026, the speed difference isnt much, in fact Streams in my opinion are better as they take care of everything for you, using portable techniques. 
In Short, use Streams when you dont have a manual and/or easy to write technnique to safely do IO, and use the println/getline when thats not the case or if you just 
dont care (what you are trying to do is not important, so its acceptable for things to go wrong), though, I think thats rare. Use streams with println or getline
((std::println(std::cout, "string") or std::getline(std::cin, destination_variable)) if you like the formating but also want everything to be taken care of.

Note: while Println is more typesafe, they dont take care of low level mishaps as well as streams can. getline is actually less type safe than streams.
Using them with streams is best because you get the best of both worlds and dont have to think about things too much because as of 4-20-2026, unless you are not
doing actual file IO ( you are instead reading or printing to a terminal ), the overhead is really not that much, since FILE IO is heavy by nature (as of 4-20-2026). 
